ator              = \n| based_on             = <!-- {{Based on|Lego Masters}} -->\n| developer            = \n| writer               = \n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = \n| creative_director    = \n| presenter            = [[Hamish Blake]]\n| starring             = \n| judges               = Ryan ''\"The Brickman\"'' McNaught\n| voices               = <!-- Organized by broadcast credit order, with new main cast added to the end of the list -->\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = \n| opentheme            = \n| endtheme             = \n| composer             = \n| country              = [[Australia]]\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = 1\n| num_episodes         = 9 <!--- (as of 14 May 2019) --->\n| list_episodes        = \n| executive_producer   = \n| producer             = \n| location             =\n| runtime              = 90 mins (including ads)\n| company              = [[Endemol Shine Australia]]\n| network              = [[Nine Network]]\n| picture_format       = {{Plainlist|\n*[[576i]] ([[SDTV]])\n*[[1080i]] ([[high-definition television|HDTV]])\n}}\n| audio_format         = [[Stereo]]\n| first_aired          = 28 April 2019\n| last_aired           = present\n| related              = <!-- To be used only for remakes, spin-offs, and adaptations -->\n| website              =\n| production_website   =\n}}\n\n'''''Lego Masters''''' is an Australian reality television show based on the [[Lego Masters (British TV series)|British series of the same name]] in which teams compete to build the best [[Lego]] project. It is hosted by [[Hamish Blake]] and judged by Lego designer Ryan \"The Brickman\" McNaught. The series premiered on 28 April 2019 on [[Nine Network]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2019/04/airdate-lego-masters.html|title=Airdate: Lego Masters|publisher=TV Tonight|first=David|last=Knox|date=15 April 2019|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\n\nThe series pits eight teams of two who work to overcome a variety of different challenges, focusing primarily on three criteria; storytelling ability, technical abilities and overall aesthetic. Outside of this criteria, the contestants have free rein on what tasks they wish to undertake for the challenges.\n\nEach episode primarily consists of two challenges; an advantage challenge and an elimination challenge. The two best teams of the day are called forward, in which the judge will award one team with a victory.\n\nIn advantage challenges, contestants battle it out to either gain an advantage in the next elimination challenge, such as extra time, or gain immunity from an elimination challenge.\n\nIn elimination challenges, much alike the two tops teams, the judge critically analyse all aspects of the builds against the main criteria, but also select the bottom two teams. The Judge is then tasked with choosing which team will be eliminated from the competition.\n\nEach team is eliminated until three teams remain for the finale build, in which the last three teams are given \"free reign\" to choose whatever they wish to impress the judges, and 250 members of the public.\n\nThe team who wins the series will receive $100,000 AUD and a specially made Lego Masters Australia 20XX trophy.\n\n==Production==\n\nAuditions for the series opened in June 2018, however no network had commissioned it at that time, filming would take place between October and December.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2018/06/auditions-lego-masters.html|title=Auditions: LEGO Masters|publisher=TV Tonight|first=David|last=Knox|date=21 June 2018|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref> The series was commissioned in July 2018 by the [[Nine Network]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2018/07/lego-masters-confirmed-for-nine.html|title=LEGO Masters confirmed for Nine|publisher=TV Tonight|first=David|last=Knox|date=3 July 2018|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nineentertainmentco.com.au/2018/07/02/16/52/nine-commissions-lego-masters-for-australia|title=Nine Commissions Lego Masters For Australia|publisher=nineentertainmentco.com.au|date=3 July 2018|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref> The series was officially confirmed at Nine's Upfronts in October 2018, also announcing the series will be hosted Hamish Blake.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2018/10/upfronts-2019-nine-seachange-australian-open-lego-masters-bad-mothers.html|title=Upfronts 2019: Nine: SeaChange, Australian Open, Lego Masters, Bad Mothers.|publisher=TV Tonight|first=David|last=Knox|date=17 October 2018|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nineentertainmentco.com.au/2018/11/02/11/02/lego-masters-provides-point-of-difference-to-nines-other-consistent-reality-formats|title=Nine 2019 Upfront: Lego Masters Provides Point Of Difference To Nine's Other Consistent Reality Formats|publisher=nineentertainmentco.com.au|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first season was sponsored by [[Lego]], [[Honda]], [[Kmart (Australia)|Kmart]] and [[The a2 Milk Company]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adnews.com.au/news/nine-reveals-sponsors-for-debut-season-of-lego-masters|title=Nine reveals sponsors for debut season of Lego Masters|publisher=Adnews|first=Josh|last=Mcdonnell|date=24 April 2019|accessdate=26 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nDue to the success of the series, In May 2019 the series was renewed for a second season which will film later in 2019 set to air in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mumbrella.com.au/nine-renews-lego-masters-for-a-second-season-579101|title=Nine renews Lego Masters for a second season|publisher=Mumbrella|first=Hannah|last=Blackiston|date=13 May 2019|accessdate=14 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://9now.nine.com.au/lego-masters/lego-masters-season-2-two-apply-applications/34694575-e4f7-447e-b3c4-d24cb8debc10|title=Apply to be part of Lego Masters second season|publisher=Nine|date=13 May 2019|accessdate=14 May 2019}}</ref> On 16 October 2019, the second season was officially confirmed at Nine's upfronts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2019/10/upfronts-2020-nine-informer-3838-halifax-returning-reality-juggernauts.html|title=Upfronts 2020: Nine: Informer 3838, Halifax, returning reality juggernauts.|publisher=TV Tonight|first=David|last=Knox|date=16 October 2019|accessdate=17 October 2019}}</ref> The second season will begin airing on 19 April 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2020/03/returning-lego-masters.html|title=Returning: Lego Masters|publisher=TV Tonight|first=David|last=Knox|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Series overview==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" rowspan=2| Season\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Episodes\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Originally aired\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Result\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Season premiere]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Season finale]]\n! scope=\"col\" | Winning team\n! scope=\"col\" | Prize\n|-\n| style=\"background:#FF5F5F; height:10px;\"|\n! scope=\"row\" | <center>[[Lego Masters (Australian season 1)|1]]</center>\n| 9\n| 28 April 2019\n| 14 May 2019\n| Henry & Cade\n| rowspan=2| $100,000\n|-\n| style=\"background:#3EB489; height:10px;\"|\n! scope=\"row\" | <center>2</center>\n| TBA\n| 19 April 2020\n| TBA\n| TBA\n|}\n\n==Season details==\n===Season 1 (2019)===\n{{main|Lego Masters (Australian season 1)}}\n\nThe first season aired on 28 April 2019 and ended on 14 May 2019. The season was won by Henry and Cade and received  $100,000 in prize money.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://amp.nine.com.au/article/c5cf7b0a-0ef3-4be3-9caf-d3766a644d2e|title= 'LEGO Masters' 2019: Henry and Cade win, reveal how they'll spend $100,000 prize money|publisher=TV Tonight|first=Aine|last=Ryan|date=14 May 2019|accessdate=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|- valig