cef2; color:black;\"| Premiere date\n! scope=\"col\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width:8em; background:#cecef2; color:black;\"| Premiere<br />ratings\n! scope=\"col\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width:4em; background:#cecef2; color:black;\"| Rank\n! scope=\"col\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em; background:#cecef2; color:black;\"| Finale date\n! scope=\"col\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width:8em; background:#cecef2; color:black;\"| '''{{nowrap|Finale ratings}}'''<br />''<small>{{nowrap|(Grand final)}}</small>''\n! scope=\"col\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width:4em; background:#cecef2; color:black;\"| Rank\n! scope=\"col\" scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#CECEF2; color:black;\"| '''{{nowrap|Finale ratings}}'''<br />''<small>{{nowrap|(Winner announced)}}</small>''\n! scope=\"col\" scope=\"col\" style=\"width:4em; background:#cecef2; color:black;\"| Rank\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#white;\"| [[Lego Masters (Australian season 1)|'''1''']]\n| 9\n| 28 April 2019\n| 1.377\n| style=\"background:#F0F8FF\"| '''#1'''\n| 14 May 2019\n| 1.249\n| style=\"background:#F0F8FF\"| '''#2'''\n| 1.493\n| style=\"background:#F0F8FF\"| '''#1'''\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2019/04/sunday-28-april-2019.html|title=Sunday 28 April 2019|publisher=TV Tonight|first=David|last=Knox|date=29 April 2019|accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2019/05/tuesday-14-may-2019.html|title=Tuesday 14 May 2019|publisher=TV Tonight|first=David|last=Knox|date=15 May 2019|accessdate=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#white;\"| [[Lego Masters (Australian season 2)|'''2''']]\n| TBA\n| 19 April 2020\n| TBA\n| style=\"background:#F0F8FF\"| '''TBA'''\n| 2020\n| TBA\n| style=\"background:#F0F8FF\"| '''TBA'''\n| TBA\n| style=\"background:#F0F8FF\"| '''TBA'''\n|\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Nominee\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2019\n| [[AACTA Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2019/12/aacta-awards-2019-winners.html|title=2019 AACTA Awards|publisher=Tvtonight.com.au|accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>\n| Best Entertainment Program\n| ''Lego Masters''\n| {{win}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2020\n| [[Brunico Communications#Realscreen|Realscreen Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Knox|first=David|url=https://tvtonight.com.au/2020/01/lego-masters-australia-wins-us-award.html|title=Lego Masters Australia wins US award|date=30 January 2020|publisher=[[TV Tonight]]|website=tvtonight.com.au|accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n| Best Competition: Quiz or Game Show\n| ''Lego Masters''\n| {{win}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Lego Masters}}\n{{Nine Network programming}}\n\n[[Category:Nine Network shows]]\n[[Category:Australian television series based on British television series]]\n[[Category:2019 Australian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s Australian television series]]\n[[Category:Australian reality television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series by Endemol]]\n[[Category:Lego television series]]\n", "name_user": "175.33.237.144", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eSeason 1 (2019))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lego_Masters_(Australian_TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Heavy Metal Parking Lot", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Heavy Metal Parking Lot\n| image          = Heavy_Metal_Parking_Lot_movie_poster.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[John Heyn]] and [[Jeff Krulik]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = \n| starring       = \n| music          =\n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = 1986\n| runtime        = 17 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       =  English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n| followed_by    = \n}}\n\n'''''Heavy Metal Parking Lot''''' is a 1986 [[Documentary film|documentary]] short produced by [[Jeff Krulik]] and John Heyn. The film features interviews with several small groups of young [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] fans gathered for a [[tailgate party]] in the parking lot outside the [[Capital Centre (Landover, Maryland)|Capital Centre]] in [[Landover, Maryland]] on May 31, 1986, as they prepare for a [[Judas Priest]]/[[Dokken]] concert being held there later that evening.\n\n==Reputation==\nBy the early 1990s, ''Heavy Metal Parking Lot'' had become an [[underground film|underground]] cult-classic, usually traded on [[Bootleg recording|bootleg]] [[VHS]] videotapes. It was reportedly a favorite on the [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] tour bus, among many other bands. Due to growing popularity of the film, music copyright issues arose between the producers and Judas Priest, though they were eventually resolved. The film has been referred to as the \"[[Citizen Kane]]\" of Wasted Teenage Metal.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Deranged True Story Of Heavy Metal Parking Lot |url=https://theconcourse.deadspin.com/the-deranged-true-story-of-heavy-metal-parking-lot-the-1758026762 |website=Deadspin |publisher=GawkerMedia}}</ref>\n\n==Sequels==\nKrulik and Heyn attempted to follow up ''Heavy Metal Parking Lot'' with ''Monster Truck Parking Lot'' in 1988, which showed fans of a [[monster truck]] rally, but the film was unfinished and unreleased. They then created ''Neil Diamond Parking Lot'' (1996) which showed fans before a [[Neil Diamond]] concert at the same Capital Centre parking lot, ten years after the original.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Top Three Moments Inspired by Heavy Metal Parking Lot |url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/blogs/artsdesk/film/2011/06/17/the-top-three-moments-inspired-by-heavy-metal-parking-lot/ |publisher=Washington City Paper |work=Arts Desk |first=Ryan |last=Little |date=June 17, 2011 |access-date=2015-07-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714212351/http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/blogs/artsdesk/film/2011/06/17/the-top-three-moments-inspired-by-heavy-metal-parking-lot/ |archive-date=2015-07-14 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 1999, they created ''[[Harry Potter]] Parking Lot''.<ref name=\"the stranger\">{{cite web |title=Heavy Metal Rules, All That Punk Shit Sucks |url=http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/heavy-metal-rules-all-that-punk-shit-sucks/Content?oid=8196040 |publisher=The Stranger |author=Kelly O |date=May 18, 2011 |access-date=2015-07-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524044800/http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/heavy-metal-rules-all-that-punk-shit-sucks/Content?oid=8196040 |archive-date=2011-05-24 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nKrulik and Heyn created and co-produced the 2004 TV series ''Parking Lot'' in association with [[Radical Media]], which was broadcast on [[Trio (TV network)|Trio]]. The series showed enthusiasts of various bands (like [[Phish]]) and activities (like [[surfing]]). Eight episodes were produced.\n\nIn 2006, a sequel of sorts was released by [[SnagFilms]], entitled ''Heavy Metal Parking Lot Alumni: Where Are They Now''. The 19-minute film looks at the adult lives of several of the young people featured in the original 1986 film.<ref>{{cite web |title=Heavy Metal Parking Lot Alumni: Where Are They Now (2006) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ueTZjqxMOh4 |publisher=[[SnagFilms]] |access-date=2019-09-20}}</ref>\n\n==2006 DVD release==\nIn May 2006, the documentary was finally released on [[DVD]], to coincide with the 20th anniversary of its filming. The DVD version contains the original 17-minute film, as well as 2 hours of bonus features that were left out of the original version and finally an interview with the infamous \"Zebra-man\" (a 22-year-old at the time), whom Krulik and Heyn tracked down and interviewed in the summer of 1999, 13 years after the original filming.<ref name=\"the stranger\" />\n\n==Cultural references==\n* The music video for the 2000 song \"[[Flavor of the Weak]]\" by [[American Hi-Fi]] is a conscious homage to ''Heavy Metal Parking Lot'', featuring the band members and others dressed as specific people from the documentary, and spouting variations on some of the same dialogue.<ref name=\"the stranger\" />\n* The music video for the 2005 song \"[[Just Want You to Know]]\" by the [[Backstreet Boys]] also references ''Heavy Metal Parking Lot''.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Must List: October 7, 2005 |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2005/09/30/must-list-october-7-2005 |publisher=Entertainment Weekly |access-date=2015-07-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924052858/http://www.ew.com/article/2005/09/30/must-list-october-7-2005 |archive-date=2015-09-24 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* The 2019 [[Steel Panther]] [[Heavy Metal Rules|album]] is named after the \"philosophy\" of the \"Zebra-man\"<ref name=\"Kerrang!\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kerrang.com/reviews/album-review-steel-panther-heavy-metal-rules/|title=Album Review: Steel Panther \u2013 Heavy Metal Rules|work=[[Kerrang!]]|last=Morton|first=Luke|date=September 24, 2019|accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.heavymetalparkinglot.com/|Heavy Metal Parking Lot}}\n* {{IMDb title|0322526|Heavy Metal Parking Lot}}\n* {{Amg movie|261425|Heavy Metal Parking Lot}}\n*[https://www.amazon.com/Heavy-Metal-Parking/dp/B000HT384Y DVD release]\n*[http://www.jeffkrulik.com filmmaker Jeff Krulik's website]\n*[http://efilmcritic.com/review.php?movie=14515 Review by Lucas Stensland]\n*[http://dc.metblogs.com/2006/05/31/qa-heavy-metal-parking-lot-20th-anniversary/ Q&A: Heavy Metal Parking Lot 20th Anniversary by Metroblogging DC]\n*[http://www.yuppiepunk.org/2008/10/heavy-metal-parking-lot.html Q&A with director Jeff Krulik]\n*[https://www.flickr.com/photos/8832088@N05/sets/72157609835935213/ Heavy Metal Parking Lot novelty trading cards]\n\n{{Judas Priest}}\n\n[[Category:1986 films]]\n[[Category:American short films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about heavy metal music and musicians]]\n[[Category:Judas Priest]]\n[[Category:Prince George's County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Films set in Maryland]]\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:1980s documentary films]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1986]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about Maryland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Heavy Metal Parking Lot\n| image          = Heavy_Metal_Parking_Lot_movie_poster.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[John Heyn]] and [[Jeff Krulik]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = \n| starring       = \n| music          =\n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = 1986\n| runtime        = 17 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       =  English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n| followed_by    = \n}}\n\n'''''Heavy Metal Parking Lot''''' is a 1986 [[Documentary film|documentary]] short produced by [[Jeff Krulik]] and John Heyn. The film features interviews with several small groups of young [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] fans gathered for a [[tailgate party]] in the parking lot outside the [[Capital Centre]] in [[Landover, Maryland]] on May 31, 1986, as they prepare for a [[Judas Priest]]/[[Dokken]] concert being held there later that evening.\n\n==Reputation==\nBy the early 1990s, ''Heavy Metal Parking Lot'' had become an [[underground film|underground]] cult-classic, usually traded on [[Bootleg recording|bootleg]] [[VHS]] videotapes. It was reportedly a favorite on the [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] tour bus, among many other bands. Due to growing popularity of the film, music copyright issues arose between the producers and Judas Priest, though they were eventually resolved. The film has been referred to as the \"[[Citizen Kane]]\" of Wasted Teenage Metal.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Deranged True Story Of Heavy Metal Parking Lot |url=https://theconcourse.deadspin.com/the-deranged-true-story-of-heavy-metal-parking-lot-the-1758026762 |website=Deadspin |publisher=GawkerMedia}}</ref>\n\n==Sequels==\nKrulik and Heyn attempted to follow up ''Heavy Metal Parking Lot'' with ''Monster Truck Parking Lot'' in 1988, which showed fans of a [[monster truck]] rally, but the film was unfinished and unreleased. They then created ''Neil Diamond Parking Lot'' (1996) which showed fans before a [[Neil Diamond]] concert at the same Capital Centre parking lot, ten years after the original.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Top Three Moments Inspired by Heavy Metal Parking Lot |url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/blogs/artsdesk/film/2011/06/17/the-top-three-moments-inspired-by-heavy-metal-parking-lot/ |publisher=Washington City Paper |work=Arts Desk |first=Ryan |last=Little |date=June 17, 2011 |access-date=2015-07-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714212351/http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/blogs/artsdesk/film/2011/06/17/the-top-three-moments-inspired-by-heavy-metal-parking-lot/ |archive-date=2015-07-14 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 1999, they created ''[[Harry Potter]] Parking Lot''.<ref name=\"the stranger\">{{cite web |title=Heavy Metal Rules, All That Punk Shit Sucks |url=http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/heavy-metal-rules-all-that-punk-shit-sucks/Content?oid=8196040 |publisher=The Stranger |author=Kelly O |date=May 18, 2011 |access-date=2015-07-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524044800/http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/heavy-metal-rules-all-that-punk-shit-sucks/Content?oid=8196040 |archive-date=2011-05-24 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nKrulik and Heyn created and co-produced the 2004 TV series ''Parking Lot'' in association with [[Radical Media]], which was broadcast on [[Trio (TV network)|Trio]]. The series showed enthusiasts of various bands (like [[Phish]]) and activities (like [[surfing]]). Eight episodes were produced.\n\nIn 2006, a sequel of sorts was released by [[SnagFilms]], entitled ''Heavy Metal Parking Lot Alumni: Where Are They Now''. The 19-minute film looks at the adult lives of several of the young people featured in the original 1986 film.<ref>{{cite web |title=Heavy Metal Parking Lot Alumni: Where Are They Now (2006) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ueTZjqxMOh4 |publisher=[[SnagFilms]] |access-date=2019-09-20}}</ref>\n\n==2006 DVD release==\nIn May 2006, the documentary was finally released on [[DVD]], to coincide with the 20th anniversary of its filming. The DVD version contains the original 17-minute film, as well as 2 hours of bonus features that were left out of the original version and finally an interview with the infamous \"Zebra-man\" (a 22-year-old at the time), whom Krulik and Heyn tracked down and interviewed in the summer of 1999, 13 years after the original filming.<ref name=\"the stranger\" />\n\n==Cultural references==\n* The music video for the 2000 song \"[[Flavor of the Weak]]\" by [[American Hi-Fi]] is a conscious homage to ''Heavy Metal Parking Lot'', featuring the band members and others dressed as specific people from the documentary, and spouting variations on some of the same dialogue.<ref name=\"the stranger\" />\n* The music video for the 2005 song \"[[Just Want You to Know]]\" by the [[Backstreet Boys]] also references ''Heavy Metal Parking Lot''.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Must List: October 7, 2005 |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2005/09/30/must-list-october-7-2005 |publisher=Entertainment Weekly |access-date=2015-07-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924052858/http://www.ew.com/article/2005/09/30/must-list-october-7-2005 |archive-date=2015-09-24 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* The 2019 [[Steel Panther]] [[Heavy Metal Rules|album]] is named after the \"philosophy\" of the \"Zebra-man\"<ref name=\"Kerrang!\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kerrang.com/reviews/album-review-steel-panther-heavy-metal-rules/|title=Album Review: Steel Panther \u2013 Heavy Metal Rules|work=[[Kerrang!]]|last=Morton|first=Luke|date=September 24, 2019|accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.heavymetalparkinglot.com/|Heavy Metal Parking Lot}}\n* {{IMDb title|0322526|Heavy Metal Parking Lot}}\n* {{Amg movie|261425|Heavy Metal Parking Lot}}\n*[https://www.amazon.com/Heavy-Metal-Parking/dp/B000HT384Y DVD release]\n*[http://www.jeffkrulik.com filmmaker Jeff Krulik's website]\n*[http://efilmcritic.com/review.php?movie=14515 Review by Lucas Stensland]\n*[http://dc.metblogs.com/2006/05/31/qa-heavy-metal-parking-lot-20th-anniversary/ Q&A: Heavy Metal Parking Lot 20th Anniversary by Metroblogging DC]\n*[http://www.yuppiepunk.org/2008/10/heavy-metal-parking-lot.html Q&A with director Jeff Krulik]\n*[https://www.flickr.com/photos/8832088@N05/sets/72157609835935213/ Heavy Metal Parking Lot novelty trading cards]\n\n{{Judas Priest}}\n\n[[Category:1986 films]]\n[[Category:American short films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about heavy metal music and musicians]]\n[[Category:Judas Priest]]\n[[Category:Prince George's County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Films set in Maryland]]\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:198