{"title_page": "Tata Group", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Tata & Sons|the parent company|Tata Sons}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Short description|Indian multinational conglomerate company}} \n{{Infobox company\n| name = Tata Group\n| logo = [[File:Tata logo.svg|150px]]\n| image = Bombay House, Tata Group Headquarters in Mumbai.jpg\n| image_caption = Tata Group's headquarters, the [[Bombay House]]\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| industry = [[Conglomerate (company)|Conglomerate]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1868}}\n| founder = [[Jamsetji Tata]]\n| location = [[Bombay House]], [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = [[Natarajan Chandrasekaran]] {{small|([[chairman]])}}<ref>{{cite web | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/tata-vs-mistry-supreme-court-stays-nclat-order-favouring-cyrus-mistry/articleshow/73184138.cms | title=Supreme Court stays NCLAT order restoring Cyrus Mistry as Tata Sons Executive Chairman | publisher=ET News | date=11 January 2020 | accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n| products = {{hlist \n  | [[Automotive]] \n  | [[Airlines]] \n  | [[Chemicals]]\n  | [[Arms industry|Defense]] \n  | [[Fast-moving consumer goods|FMCG]] \n  | [[Electric Utility]]\n  | [[Finance]] \n  | [[Home appliances]]\n  | [[Hospitality industry|Hospitality]] \n  | [[IT Services]] \n  | [[Retail]] \n  | [[Real estate]] \n  | [[Steel]] \n  | [[Telecommunications|Telecom]]\n  }}\n| revenue = {{Profit}} {{US$|113.0 billion|link=yes}}<ref name=\"Tata Financials\">{{cite web |url=https://www.tata.com/business/overview|title=Tata Group Business Overview |work=Tata Group}}</ref>\n| revenue_year = 2019\n| assets = \n| assets_year = \n| owner = [[Tata Sons]]\n| num_employees = 722,281 (2019)<ref name=\"Tata Financials\"/>\n| subsid = [[List of entities associated with Tata Group|List of subsidiaries]]\n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.tata.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Tata Group''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|t|\u0251\u02d0|t|\u0251\u02d0}}) is an Indian multinational [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] [[holding company]] headquartered in [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]. Founded in 1868 by [[Jamsetji Tata]], the company gained international recognition after purchasing several global companies. One of India's largest conglomerates, Tata Group is owned by [[Tata Sons]].<ref name=\"forbes2011\">{{cite book|last1=Pocha|first1=Jehangir|title=Tata Sons: Passing the Baton|date=12 December 2011|publisher=Forbes India|url=http://www.forbesindia.com/printcontent/31052|accessdate=25 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tata Sons Limited vs The Deputy Cit, Special Range-1 on 28 April, 2006|url=https://indiankanoon.org/docfragment/399270/?big=0&formInput=public%20trusts|website=www.indiankanoon.org|publisher=Civil court, Mumbai|accessdate=25 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nEach Tata company operates independently under the guidance and supervision of its own board of directors and shareholders. Significant Tata companies and subsidiaries include [[Tata Chemicals]], [[Tata Communications]], [[Tata Consultancy Services]], [[Tata Consumer Products]], [[Tata Elxsi]], [[Tata Motors]], [[Tata Power]], [[Tata Steel]], [[Voltas]], [[Tata Cliq]], [[Titan Company|Titan]], [[Trent (Westside)]], [[Taj Hotels]], and [[Jaguar Land Rover]]\n\n==History==\n\n=== 1868\u20131904 ===\nAt the age of 29, [[Jamsetji Tata]] worked in his father's company. In 1870 with Rs.21,000 capital, he founded a trading company. Further he bought a bankrupt oil mill at [[Chinchpokli]] and converted it into a cotton mill, under the name Alexandra Mill which he sold for a profit after 2 years. In 1874, he set up another cotton mill at [[Nagpur]] named Empress Mill. He dreamed of achieving 4 goals, setting up an iron and steel company, a unique hotel, a world-class learning institution and a hydro-electric plant. During his lifetime, in 1903, the [[The Taj Mahal Palace Hotel|Taj Mahal Hotel]] at [[Colaba]] waterfront was opened making it the first hotel with electricity in India.\n\n=== 1904\u20131938 ===\nAfter Jamsetji's death, his older son [[Dorabji Tata]] became the Chairman in 1904. Sir Dorabji established the Tata Iron and Steel company (TISCO), now known as [[Tata Steel]] in 1907. Marking the group's global ambitions, Tata Limited opened its first overseas office in [[London]]. Following the founder's goals, Western India's first hydro plant was brought to life, giving birth to [[Tata Power]]. Yet another dream, Indian Institute of Science was established with the first batch admitted in 1911.\n\n=== 1938\u20131991 ===\n[[J. R. D. Tata|JRD Tata]] was made Chairman of the Tata Group in 1938. Under his chairmanship, the assets of the Tata Group grew from US$101 million to over US$5 billion. Starting with 14 enterprises, upon his departure half a century later in 1988, Tata Sons had grown to a conglomerate of 95 enterprises. These enterprises consisted of ventures that the company had either started or in which they held controlling interest. New sectors such as chemicals, technology, cosmetics, marketing, engineering, and manufacturing, tea, and software services earned them recognition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Tata-Group|title=Tata Group {{!}} History, Companies, Subsidiaries, & Facts|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nIn 1952, JRD founded an airline, known as [[Air India|Tata Air Services]] (later renamed Tata Airlines). In 1953, the Government of India passed the Air Corporations Act and purchased a majority stake in the carrier from [[Tata Sons]], though JRD Tata would continue as Chairman till 1977.\n\nIn 1945, [[Tata Motors]] was founded, first focused on locomotives. In 1954, it entered the commercial vehicle market after forming a joint venture with [[Daimler-Benz]]. In 1968, [[Tata Consultancy Services]] was founded.\n\n=== From 1991 till present ===\nIn 1991, [[Ratan Tata]] was made Chairman of Tata Group. This was also the year of [[Economic liberalisation in India|economic liberalization in India]], opening up the market to foreign competitors. During this time, Tata Group began to acquire a number of companies, including [[Tetley]] (2000), [[Tata Steel Europe|Corus Group]] (2007), and [[Jaguar Cars|Jaguar]] and [[Land Rover]] (2008). In 2017, [[Natarajan Chandrasekaran]] was appointed chairman.DEEWDASFAFDDDSDCC\n\n==Chairman==\nThe Chairman of [[Tata Sons]] is usually the Chairman of the Tata Group.\n*[[Jamsetji Tata]] (1868\u20131904)\n* [[Sir Dorab Tata]] (1904\u20131932)\n* [[Nowroji Saklatwala]] (1932\u20131938)\n* [[Jehangir Ratanji Dadabhoy Tata|JRD Tata]] (1938\u20131991)\n* [[Ratan Tata]] (1991\u20132012)\n* [[Cyrus Mistry]] (2012\u20132016)\n* [[Ratan Tata]](2016\u20132017)\n* [[Natarajan Chandrasekaran]] (2017 till date)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/tata-vs-mistry-supreme-court-stays-nclat-order-favouring-cyrus-mistry/articleshow/73184138.cms|title=Supreme Court Stays NCLAT order restoring Cyrus Mistry as Chairman|date=11 January 2020|publisher=|via=The Economic Times}}</ref>\n\n==Subsidiaries==\n{{main|List of entities associated with Tata Group}}\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| header = \n| width = 200\n| image1 = Bombay house mast.jpg\n| caption1 = [[Bombay House]], the head office of Tata Group\n| image2 =\n| caption2 = Tata Bus\n| image3 = 2017-03-07 Geneva Motor Show 1068.JPG\n| caption3 = [[Tata Tigor]]\n| image4 = TataTea.JPG\n| caption4 = Packets of [[Tata Tea]]\n| image5 = Himalayan.JPG\n| caption5 = Himalayan\u2014Tata mineral water\n| image6 = Shuttle at Madrid airport.jpg\n| caption6 = Tata bus in Madrid, Spain\n| image7 = TATA_XENON.jpg\n| caption7 = Thai-assembled Tata Xenon pickup truck\n| image8 = Taj Mahal Palace Hotel.jpg\n| caption8 = [[The Taj Mahal Palace Hotel]], owned by a Tata subsidiary\n| total_width = \n| alt1 = \n}}\nThis section lists the Tata companies and details their business:\n\n'''Chemicals'''\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Tata Chemicals]]\n* Advinus Therapeutics\n* [[Brunner Mond]]\n* General Chemical Industrial Products\n* Magadi Soda Company\n* Rallis India\n* Tata Pigments Limited\n{{colend}}\n'''Consumer Products'''\n{{Div col}}\n* Casa D\u00e9cor\n* [[Eight O'Clock Coffee]]\n* [[Fastrack (fashion accessories)|Fastrack]], youth fashion brand\n* Himalayan, mineral water brand\n* [[I-shakti]]\n* Infiniti Retail ([[Crom\u0101]])\n* [[Landmark Bookstores]]\n* [[Tanishq]]\n* Tata Ceramics\n* [[Tata Coffee]]\n* [[Tata Consumer Products]], second-largest global manufacturer of tea products\n* Tata Industries\n* Tata International Ltd.\n* Tata Refractories\n* [[Tata Salt]]\n* [[Tata Sky]]\n* [[Tata Starbucks]], a 50:50 joint venture company, owned by Starbucks Corporation and Tata Global Beverages\n* [[Tata Swach]]\n* Tata Zoya\n* [[Tetley]]\n* [[Titan Industries]]\n** Titan Eye Plus (Titan Eye+), Titan Industries optical stores \n* [[Voltas]], consumer electronics company\n* [[Trent (Westside)|Westside]]\n{{colend}}\n'''Energy'''\n{{Div col}}\n* Hooghly Met Coke and Power Company\n* Jamshedpur Utilities and Services Company\n* Powerlinks Transmission\n* Tata Petrodyne\n* [[Tata Power]], one of the largest private sector power companies\n* Tata Power Delhi Distribution Ltd (formerly known as North Delhi Power Ltd)\n* [[Tata Power Solar]], started as a joint venture between [[Tata Power]] and [[BP Solar]], now a wholly owned company\n* Tata Power Trading\n* Tata Projects\n{{colend}}\n'''Engineering'''\n{{Div col|colwidth=}}\n* Hispano Carrocera\n* TAL Manufacturing Solutions\n* TASL (Tata Advanced Systems Limited)\n* Tata Advanced Materials\n* Tata Advanced Systems\n* Tata AutoComp Systems Limited (TACO)\n* Tata Consulting Engineers Limited\n* [[Tata Marcopolo]]\n* Tata Cummins\n* [[Tata Motors]], India's largest 